<div id="p1872" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#4</span> <a href="viewtopic.php?pid=1872#p1872">2011-01-22 11:36:15</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postbody">
				<div class="postleft">
					<dl>
						<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=90580">jch</a></strong></dt>
						<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					</dl>
				</div>
				<div class="postright">
					<h3>Re: BT-radio, DHT extension</h3>
					<div class="postmsg">
						<p>What you appear to be doing is naive flooding (with duplicate detection) of magnet links in a subset of the DHT.&#160; The only reason why you&#039;re using the DHT is that it gives you liveness information for free -- other than that, your protocol is completely distinct from the DHT.</p><p>Why not use TCP?&#160; You&#039;re presumably only flooding to a small set of neighbours, and your flooding traffic will end up being pretty high, so using a congestion-controlled, reliable protocol might be a good idea.</p><p>I would suggest that you have a look at Gnutella and other gossip protocols before you continue.</p><p>--jch</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postfoot clearb">
				<div class="postfootleft"><p><span>Offline</span></p></div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

<div id="p1876" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#5</span> <a href="viewtopic.php?pid=1876#p1876">2011-01-22 14:22:04</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postbody">
				<div class="postleft">
					<dl>
						<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89620">roee88</a></strong></dt>
						<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					</dl>
				</div>
				<div class="postright">
					<h3>Re: BT-radio, DHT extension</h3>
					<div class="postmsg">
						<p>It seems like content discovery is a hot topic lately.</p><p>If I understand correctly, the target is discovering new content related to anything the user has showed interest in.<br />Assuming user interest could be decided by latest downloads, Has anyone considered a torrent-exchange LTEP extension?<br />I&#039;m not getting into details but in short: Allow peers in the same swarm to exchange info hashes of their currently loaded torrents (add some of the discovered torrents to keep some level of privacy). Rank items by the number of peers that sent them. Reflect any item with rank above TBD to the user as &quot;Related downloads&quot;.</p><p>I personally don&#039;t like the idea of the DHT responsible for anything other than discovery of swarm peers. (As a side note, I would love to see <a href="http://forum.bittorrent.org/viewtopic.php?pid=1776#p1776">decentralized feeds over virtual torrents</a>. &#039;related feeds&#039; discovery, if necessary, could use the same extension described above).</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postfoot clearb">
				<div class="postfootleft"><p><span>Offline</span></p></div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

